Iris domestica

(L.) Goldblatt & Mabb [the name 

Belamcanda chinensis

(L.) DC (
Iridaceae
) was recorded in Chinese Pharmacopoeia for 2020] belongs to the family 
Iridaceae
and is widely distributed in eastern Asia. Its rhizomes have been historically used as a traditional Chinese folk medicine to treat sore throat, cough, tonsillitis and pharyngitis (

). Pharmacological research has shown that 

I. domestica

is often used with other herbs as antipyretic agents, antidotes, expectorants, antiphlogistics, and analgesics (

). Prior phytochemical investigation of this plant demonstrates that flavonoids, especially isoflavones, are the primary active ingredient of 

I. domestica

(Wo´zniak and Matkowski, 2015). Isoflavones and their glycosides, such as tectorigenin, irigenin, tectoridin, iridin, and irisflorentin, possess a wide range of biological activities, such as anti-inflammatory (

), antioxidative (

), antiviral (

), antibacterial (

), and antitumor (

) activities. However, the applications of diverse and bioactive flavones are often limited by their poor solubility in both hydrophobic and hydrophilic media. Therefore, modification of flavonoid glycosides via acylation has become a promising approach. Previous studies have shown that fatty acid acylated flavonoid glycosides improve the lipophilicity, and biological activities of the parent flavones (

; 

; 

; 

,b; 

).

To determine the length of the fatty acid, alkaline hydrolysis by NaOH was used. Analysis of the alkaline hydrolysis products by LC–MS, reveals the molecular formulas of C 23 H 24 O 12 (MW: 492) and C 14 H 28 O 2 (MW: 228), which indicates the presence of myristic acid. Subsequently, the products of alkaline hydrolysis for 1 were isolated to yield the pure compound iristectorin A with a molecular weight of 492. For compound 1 , the characteristic signal of an anomeric proton with the coupling constant J ′′ H-1 -2’’ = 8.8 Hz demonstrates that the relative configuration of pyranohexose is β (
;
). The absolute configuration of glucopyranosyl is defined by the GC analysis of products from the acid hydrolysis and derivatization reactions by L-cysteine methyl ester hydrochloride and trimethylsilylimidazole of iristectorin A. The acid hydrolysis result indicates that glucopyranosyl is D-glc. Therefore, 1 originated from iristectorin A esterified by myristic acid. Compound 1 was named Belamcandnoate A.

Compound 2 was obtained as a pale yellow oil (MeOH). Its molecular formula, C 38 H 52 O 14 , was deduced from the HRESIMS ion at [M + H] + m/z 733.34265 (calcd 733.34298), which indicated 13 indices of hydrogen deficiency. Compared with the corresponding NMR signals of 1 , there are spectroscopic differences due to AB aromatic system signals at δ H 6.72 (1H, d, J = 2.3 Hz, H-6 ′ ), 6.66 (1H, d, J = 2.3 Hz, H-2 ′ ), δ C 104.4 (C-2 ′ ), 110.4 (C-6 ′ ) and a methoxyl group at δ H 3.78 (3H, s), δ C 55.9 (-OCH 3 ). The methoxyl group is ascribed to C-5 ′ based on the HMBC correlations from δ H 3.78 to C-5 ′ and C-2’. The above mentioned data demonstrate that the isoflavone glycoside is iridin (
). The sugar of 2 is defined as glucopranosyl by comparing the NMR data with those of glycosides in the literature (
;
). 1 H NMR data of 2 display an anomeric proton signal at δ H 5.16 (1H, d, J = 8.6 Hz, H-1 ′′ ), which reveals the β -configuration of glucose ( J ′′ 1 -2’’ > 7 Hz) (
). Using the GC analysis of acid hydrolysis products of iridin, the absolute configuration of the sugar unit is determined to be the D-configuration. Analysis of the alkaline hydrolysis products for 2 by LC–MS, reveals the same molecular weights of mw = 522 (C 24 H 26 O 13 ) and mw = 228 (C 14 H 28 O 2 ) as 1 , which indicates that iridin is esterified by myristic acid. Thus, compound 2 was named Belamcandnoate B.

Compound 3 was isolated as a pale oil. HRESIMS indicates a proton adduct ion [M + H] + at m/z 723.33417 (calcd 723.33510), which corresponds to a molecular formula of C 38 H 52 O 12 with 13 indices of hydrogen deficiency. Examination of the NMR data of compounds 3 and 1 indicates that the differences between the two compounds can be attributed to an A’ A’ B’ B’ aromatic system with signals at δ H 7.38 (2H, d, J = 10.3 Hz, H-2 ′ , 6 ′ ), 6.82 (2H, m, H-3 ′ , 5 ′ ); δ C 130.1 (C-2 ′ , 6 ′ ), 115.1 (C- 3 ′ , 5 ′ ) for 3 . Subsequently, an alkaline hydrolysis reaction was conducted, and the results of LC MS analysis show molecular weights of mw = 462 (C 22 H 22 O 11 ) and mw = 256 (C 16 H 32 O 2 ), which support that compound 3 is the palmitic acid acylated derivative of tectoridin (
). Comparison of the NMR data with those of glycosides in the literature (
;
), and the coupling constant values J ′′ 1 -2’’ = 8.9 Hz ( > 7 Hz) demonstrate that the sugar of 3 was glucopranosyl, and the relative configuration was assigned as β . An acid hydrolysis experiment shows that glucopyranosyl was D-glc. Therefore, compound 3 was named Belamcandnoate C.

Compound 4 was obtained as a pale yellow oil (MeOH). Its molecular formula, C 42 H 56 O 14 , was determined by the HRESIMS ion at [M + H] + m/z 785.37329 (calcd for 785.37428), which indicates 15 indices of hydrogen deficiency, two degrees of unsaturation higher than 1 . The NMR data ( Table 2 ) closely resembled those of 1 . The differences mainly involved two double bonds at δ H 5.28 (4H, m, H-6 ′′′ , 7 ′′′ , 9 ′′′ , 10 ′′′ ); δ C 129.7 (C-6 ′′′ ), 129.6 (C-10 ′′′ ), 127.7 (C-7 ′′′ ), 129.6 (C-9 ′′′ ), which corresponded to the degrees of unsaturation. Analysis of the alkaline hydrolysis products of 4 by LC—MS reveals molecular weights of mw = 522 (C 24 H 26 O 13 ) and mw = 280 (C 18 H 32 O 2 ), which indicates that compound 4 was an octadecadienoic acid acylated derivative of tectoridin. The 1 H– 1 H COSY correlations show two fragments: C(2 ′′′ )H 2 –C(3 ′′′ )H 2 –C(4 ′′′ ) H 2 –C(5 ′′′ )H 2 –C(6 ′′′ )H and C(7 ′′′ )H–C(8 ′′′ )H 2 –C(9 ′′′ )H–C(10 ′′′ )H. HMBC correlations from H-6 ′′′ to C-4 ′′′ , C-7 ′′′ , C-8 ′′′ , from H-10 ′′′ to C-8 ′′′ , C-9 ′′′ , C-12 ′′′ , demonstrate that the long-chain fatty acid was 6 ′′′ , 9 ′′′ -octadecadienoic acid. Moreover, the obvious upfield shift of the bisallylic methylene signal at δ C 25.2 (C-8 ′′′ ), along with the typical carbon resonances of two allylic methylenes at δ C 26.6 (C-5 ′′′ ) and δ C 26.6 (C-11 ′′′ ) indicate that the methylene interrupted double bonds were Z -configuration (
;
). Therefore, the long-chain fatty acid side chain was defined as 6? Z , 9? Z -octadecadienoic acid. Besides, the NMR data were highly similar to those of glycosides in literature (
;
), combined with the coupling constant value J = 8.8 Hz of anomeric proton, they enabled the identification of the sugar unit as β -glucose. The acid hydrolysis indicates that glucopyranosyl was D-glc. Compound 4 was defined as Belamcandnoate D.

Compound 5 was obtained as a pale oil, and the HRESIMS data displayed an [M – H] – ion at m/z 753.34924 (calcd 753.34916), which established a molecular formula of C 41 H 54 O 13 with 15 degrees of unsaturation. Considering the HRESIMS data, the molecular weight of 5 was 30 mass units less than that of 4 , which indicates the absence of a methoxy group in 5 . The comparison of the NMR data of compounds 5 and 4 reveals a difference due to different substituent groups of ring B. In the 1 H NMR spectrum, the resonances at δ H 7.05 (1H, d, J = 2.3 Hz, H- 2 ′ ), 6.95 (2H, m, H-6 ′ , 5 ′ ) are attributed to an ABX aromatic system for ring B. Comparison of the NMR data with 1 indicates that 5 and 1 share identical isoflavone glycosides. An LC MS analysis of the alkaline hydrolysis products of 5 reveals molecular weights of 492 (C 23 H 24 O 12 ) and 280 (C 18 H 32 O 2 ), which indicates that compound 5 was an octadecadienoic acid acylated derivative of iristectorin A. Similar double bonds NMR data as
4 in
side chain are displayed at δ H 5.28 (4H, m, H-6 ′′′ , 7 ′′′ , 9 ′′′ , 10 ′′′ ), δ C 129.7 (C-6 ′′′ ), 129.6 (C-10 ′′′ ), 127.8 (C-7 ′′′ ), 127.8 (C-9 ′′′ ), which supports the conclusion that 5 and 4 share the same fatty acid side chain—6 ′′′ , 9 ′′′ -octadecadienoic acid. Besides, the characteristic 13 C NMR data of two bisallylic methylenes at δ C 26.6 (C-5 ′′′ ) and δ C 26.6 (C-11 ′′′ ), and the upfield shift value of an interrupted methylene signal at δ C 25.2 (C-8 ′′′ ) are observed, which demonstrate that the geometry of double bonds Δ 6′′′, 7′′′ and Δ 9′′′, 10′′′ is Z -configuration (
;
). The relative configuration of the sugar unit is determined as the β -configuration according to the coupling constant value J ′′ 1 -2’’ = 8.6 Hz ( J ′′ 1 -2’’ > 7 Hz) (
;
). The absolute configuration of D-glc is further confirmed by acid hydrolysis using GC analysis. Compound 5 was elucidated as Belamcandnoate E.

Compound 6 was obtained as a pale oil, and its molecular formula C 40 H 52 O 12 was determined by HRESIMS with [M + Na] + ion at m/z 747.33429 (calcd 747.33510), which indicated that it was 15 indices of hydrogen deficiency. Analysis of the 1 H and 13 C NMR data of compounds 6 and 4 (except the fatty acid side chains), ascribed the differences to an A’ A’ B’ B’ aromatic system at δ H 7.38 (2H, d, J = 10.3 Hz, H-2 ′ , 6 ′ ), 6.84 (2H, d, J = 10.3 Hz, H-3 ′ , 5 ′ ); δ C 130.1 (C-2 ′ , 6 ′ ), 115.1 (C-3 ′ , 5 ′ ) for 6 . To determine the length of the fatty acid chain, alkaline hydrolysis by NaOH was performed. The LC MS analysis results displayed molecular weights of 462 (C 22 H 22 O 11 ) and 280 (C 18 H 32 O 2 ), indicating that it was the octadecadienoic acid acylated derivative of tectoridin. The NMR data of 6 reveal two double bonds at δ H 5.29 (4H, m, H-6 ′′′ , 7 ′′′ , 9 ′′′ , 10 ′′′ ), and δ C 129.7 (C-6 ′′′ ), 129.6 (C-10 ′′′ ), 127.8 (C-7 ′′′ ), 127.8 (C-9 ′′′ ), which verify that 6 and 4 share the same fatty acid side chain. The geometry configuration of the double bonds in the side chain was deduced as 6? Z , 9? Z , based on the typical 13 C NMR data of an upfield shift allylic methylene at δ C 25.2 (C-8 ′′′ ), and two bisallylic methylenes at δ C 26.6 (C- 5 ′′′ ) and δ C 26.6 (C-11 ′′′ ) (
;
). Moreover, the sugar unit NMR data in the literature (
;
), and the coupling constant value J ′′ 1 -2’’ = 8.8 Hz enabled us to determine the relative configuration of the sugar moiety as β -glucose. The D-configuration at the anomeric center of glucose was established by acid hydrolysis and GC analysis. Compound 6 was elucidated as Belamcandnoate F.

Iridin ( 1 mg ), iristectorin A ( 1.5 mg ), and tectoridin ( 1.2 mg ) were hydrolyzed with HCl (2 mol/L, 3 mL) and reacted at 90 ◦ C for 2 h, respectively. The reaction mixture was partitioned with CH 2 Cl 2 three times (5 mL × 3). After evaporating under reduced pressure, the CH 2 Cl 2 extract was analyzed by MS to find the aglycone (C 18 H 16 O 8 , M = 360). The aqueous phase extract was placed in a desiccator overnight. Then, Lcysteine methyl ester hydrochloride ( 5 mg ) and anhydrous pyridine (1 mL) were added to the aqueous layer. The mixture was vigorously stirred at 60 ◦ C for 2 h. Then, 200 μ L trimethylsilylimidazole was added to the mixture and kept at 60 ◦ C for 2 h. The solution was poured into water (3 mL), followed by extraction with hexane (3 × 5 mL). The authentic sugar (D- and L-glucoses) derivatives were obtained using the same methods. The hexane mixture (5 μ L) was analyzed by GC chromatography and subjected to an Agilent 7890A gas chromatograph with an HP-5 column ( 60 m × 0.25 mm , with a 0.25 μ m film, Dikma) and an FID detector under the following conditions: column temperature: 200–280 ◦ C; programmed increase: 10 ◦ C/min; carrier gas: N 2 (1 mL/ min); injector and detector temperature: 280 ◦ C; injection volume: 5 μ L; split ratio: 1/50. The configuration of the sugar moiety was determined by comparing the retention time with the derivatives of authentic samples. The retention times of D and L-glucose were 29.405 and 30.219 min, respectively, which helped identify the configuration of the sugar moiety of compounds 1–6 as D-glucose (
;
).

The antioxidant activities of compounds 1–6 were determined by an MDA colorimetric assay in Fe 2+ /cysteine-induced liver microsomal lipid peroxidation. Hepatic microsomes were maintained in 0.1 M PBS (pH 7.4), and the system contained 1.5 mg /mL liver microsomal protein, 0.1 μ M compounds and 200 μ M cysteine and was cultured in a 37 ◦ C water bath for 15 min FeSO 4 (50 μ M) was added into the reactions, and the plates were cultured in a 37 ◦ C water bath for an additional 15 min. The reactions were terminated by the addition of 20% TCA. The reaction mixtures were centrifuged at 2000 r/min for 10 min, and then 1 mL of each supernatant was combined with 1 mL of 0.67% TBA and cultured in a boiling water bath for 10 min. The optical density (OD) of each reaction solution was measured with a microplate reader at 532 nm . The content of MDA was used as a measure of oxidizing strength: lower MDA contents indicated stronger oxidation resistance. The concentration of MDA was obtained using the following formula: C ( n M) = [(OD– 0.006)/ 0.07] × 10, and the antioxidant activities of the compounds were calculated using the following formula: Inhibition (%) = 1–[C(sample)– C(blank))/(C(model)–C(blank))] × 100 (
;
).

